API docs by Redocly

TE REST API (1.2.2)

Authentication

The API uses HTTP bearer authentication.
You must provide the token in the Authorization header in every request (eg. Authorization: Bearer YOUR-TOKEN).
All API requests must be made over HTTPS. Calls made over plain HTTP will fail.

Authenticate.

Creates a bearer token for use in subsequent API calls.

Request Body schema: application/json
required
object (The authentication request data.)

Errors

The API uses conventional HTTP response codes to indicate the success or failure of an API request.
In general:
Codes in the 2xx range indicate success.
Codes in the 4xx range indicate an error that failed given the information provided (e.g., a required parameter was omitted, a update failed, etc.).
Codes in the 5xx range indicate an internal server error (these are rare).
Some 4xx errors that could be handled programmatically (e.g. an invalid parameter provided) include an error message that briefly explains the error reported.

The commonly used HTTP status codes are :

  • 200 - OK The request was processed as expected.
  • 400 - Bad Request The request was unacceptable, often due to missing a required parameter
  • 402 - Unauthorized No valid API key provided.
  • 402 - Request Failed The parameters were valid but the request failed.
  • 403 - Forbidden The API key doesn't have permissions to perform the request.
  • 404 - Not Found The requested resource doesn't exist.

Web Sockets

Clients may establish a Web Socket connection via a HTTP1.1 UPGRADE request.
The request must include a valid bearer token in the Authentication header (Authentication: Bearer <token>).
In addition to calling all REST methods available via HTTP, the WS clients may also subscribe to desired resources to receive updates in real time.

Note that the server will close any connection which has been inactive for 600 seconds. Therefore if the client wants to remain connected, it must send Web Socket PING messages periodically. See Section 5.5.2 of RFC6455 for more information.

If your WS client implementation does not support standard PING/PONG messages for some reason, you may emulate this behavior by sending the following dummy message to the server periodically instead: 

{  
  "id": "",  
  "method": "ping",  
  "url": ""  
}

REST via WS

A client can perform all REST operations which are available via HTTP by sending request messages in the following format: 

 {  
 "id": "123", // A unique identifier provided by the client for this request.  
 "method": "get", // May be one of "get", "post", "delete", "subscribe", "unsubscribe". 
 "url": "accounts", // The route URL (use the same route URL's you would use via HTTP). 
 "content": {} // Optional. It should contain the body of requests such as POST. 
 }

All responses from the server use the following format: 

 { 
 "id": "123", // The unique identifer provided by the client. 
 "status": 200, // The status code (HTTP status codes are used for REST responses) 
 "content": {} // Optional. May be an array of objects depending on the request. 
 }

Subscriptions

A client can subscribe to any route (available via HTTP GET) to receive updates for that particular resource. So for example, to subscribe to all accounts, the request and response would be: 

// Request  
{  
  "id": "1",  
  "method": "subscribe",  
  "url": "accounts"  
}  
// Response  
{  
  "id": "1",  
  "status": 200 // (HTTP OK status code - subscription successful)  
}

After a successful subscription, any changes to any account (available to the station) will be published in the following format: 

{  
  "id": "pub/accounts/*",  
  "status": 0, // Reserved. Currently unused.  
  "content": {  
    "type": "update", // May be one of "add", "update", "delete".  
    "data": { // The account data.  
      "acct": "SBELIC",  
      "groupId": "TOZA_GROUP",  
      "flags": 236966768  
      // Other account fields...  
    }  
  }  
}

A client may also subscribe to a specific account, for example: 

// Request  
{  
  "id": "1",  
  "method": "subscribe",  
  "url": "accounts/SBELIC" // Note the account identifier.  
}  
// Response  
{  
  "id": "1",  
  "status": 200 // (HTTP OK status code - subscription successful)  
}

And the publications would look like: 

{  
  "id": "pub/accounts/SBELIC",  
  "status": 0, // Reserved. Currently unused.  
  "content": {  
    "type": "update", // May be one of "add", "update", "delete".  
    "data": { // The account data.  
      "acct": "SBELIC",  
      "groupId": "TOZA_GROUP",  
      "flags": 236966768  
      // Other account fields...  
    }  
  }  
}

To unsubscribe, the client should send a request with the same URL but use “unsubscribe“ method instead.

The subscriptions are not persisted on the server when the connection is closed, so the client must subscribe to the data it needs after it reconnects.

Orders

Order related resources.

Get all orders.

The Orders are sent back in a list where the order record ID is in descending order, and can be filtered based on one of the following query parameters - account, group ID, destination, or clOrdId. For paginated responses, use the limit and before-id parameters.

query Parameters
account
string

An account ID for requesting orders by account.

groupId
string

A group ID for requesting orders by group ID.

destination
string

A destination for requesting orders by destination.

clOrdId
string

The client order ID.

limit
any

The maximum amount of records to fetch.

before-id
any

Fetch orders starting with the order before this ID.

filters
Array of objects (filters)

The subfilters. If not empty, only useAnd property is required, other properties are not used. Use subfilters to group filters in parentheses.

{
  • "useAnd": true,
  • "field": "string",
  • "value": null,
  • "operation": 12,
  • "filters": [
    • { }
    ]
}

The Search Info object

Search information container.

index
integer (The starting index.)
pageSize
integer (The page size (0 = unlimited).)
orderBy
string (The column name by which to order the result.)
orderAsc
boolean (Specifies whether to sort by ascending order (false = descending).)
Array of objects (filters)

The list of filters to apply.

{
  • "index": 0,
  • "pageSize": 0,
  • "orderBy": "string",
  • "orderAsc": true,
  • "filters": [
    • {
      • "useAnd": true,
      • "field": "string",
      • "value": null,
      • "operation": 12,
      • "filters": [
        • { }
        ]
      }
    ]
}
